President of Nigeria School Sport Federation (NSSF), Olabisi Joseph, said Ronke Akanbi’s record-winning run at the on-going 19th International School Sports Federation (ISF) Gymnasiade 2022 in Normandy, France has boosted the resolve of the country’s 10-man contingent. The 17-year-old Akanbi on Tuesday smashed Nigeria’s 3000m record after running 9.36.86secs to win the gold medal as the first medal to be won by any African team at the on-going championship. Joseph who led the team to the multi-sport fiesta said: “I think for us at NSSF, this is a big feat and this is what we believe can restore the lost glory of Nigeria when we expose our young athletes to international competitions.   NSSF President Joseph elected to ISF Executive Committee     Napoli lines up replacement for Osimhen     West Ham may table £20m bid for Dennis   “As part of NSSF’s plan, we decided to return Nigeria to the global family with our presence in France and we are happy that our participation has been worthwhile with what Akanbi has achieved. “I am impressed with our athletes because they have shown courage and determination in the midst of other athletes and we hope this feat in France would inspire other Nigerian students to always aim high both on track and in class.” Nigeria and 10 other African countries are competing at the global cadet championships with Uganda having the largest contingent of 40 competing in five events. Other African nations in France are Algeria, Mauritius, Senegal, Madagascar, Cote d’Ivoire, and Tanzania. The 19th edition of the ISF Gymnasiade — an international competition for 15-18-year-olds — in multiple cities across the region. More than 3,000 participants from 80 international delegations, spread over 17 disciplines (three para-sports), are in Normandy for this global sporting championship.